        "creation_date": 1590340850,
        "body": "<p>I could reproduce your problem. <\/p>\n\n<p>1 - Move your Helloer class to inside ca.company package. \nSpring classpath scanning won't work if Helloer is at the same level as ca.company and you will get some error like below:<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>This can also happen if you are @ComponentScanning a springframework package (e.g. if you put a @ComponentScan in the default package by mistake)<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>Your structure should be:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>- java\n  - ca.company\n    - config\n    - hello\n      Helloer\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>2 - With spring classpath scan working, you can remove your bean definitions from your Configuration classes, as you will get a double bean definition error. <\/p>\n\n<p>3 - Remove the annotations you added to suppress the errors in [1]. <\/p>\n",
        "answer_id": 61989635,
        "question_id": 61989286
    }],
